    "last_activity_date" : 1553579061,
    "creation_date" : 1553579061,
    "answer_id" : 55350537,
    "question_id" : 1842734,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Java also provides a nice way of calling async methods. in <strong>java.util.concurrent</strong> we have <strong>ExecutorService</strong> that helps in doing the same. Initialize your object like this -</p>\n\n<pre><code> private ExecutorService asyncExecutor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and then call the function like-</p>\n\n<pre><code>asyncExecutor.execute(() -&gt; {\n\n                        TimeUnit.SECONDS.sleep(3L);}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4086960,
      "reputation" : 939,
      "user_id" : 3356028,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/639b1e7b79803da2c4339889b5f783f3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "vitro",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3356028/vitro"
